name: Cook, Robert E.
title: Co-Founder / Serial Entrepreneur
notes: Robert E. Cook spent his career as a serial entrepreneur in computer software. His first company was VM Software (later renamed System Center / Systems Center, Inc.), which he founded in 1981; the company was listed on both the Nasdaq and New York Stock Exchanges and was sold in 1993. He is recognized on the IT History Society Honor Roll for his contributions to computing history.

name: Fargo, Thomas B.
title: Chairman of the Board (Independent Director)
notes: Admiral Thomas B. Fargo, USN (Ret.) served as Commander of U.S. Pacific Command (2002-2005) after a 35-year Navy career. After retiring from the Navy he became President of Trex Enterprises (2005-2008), then Managing Director at J.F. Lehman and Co. He has been Chairman of Hawaiian Electric Industries since May 2020, previously served as Non-Executive Chairman of Huntington Ingalls Industries (2011-2020), and chairs the USAA board. He also serves on the boards of Matson, Inc. and The Greenbrier Companies.
ngos: John M. Shalikashvili Chair in National Security Studies, National Bureau of Asian Research (2010-2016); Japan-America Society of Hawaii; I'olani School Board of Governors; Hawaii Pacific University Board of Trustees

name: Gammill, Lee M. Jr.
title: Executive Vice President (retired)
notes: Lee M. Gammill Jr. served as Executive Vice President at New York Life Insurance Company during the early 1990s. He was a senior officer involved in company compliance and strategic decisions, including serving on the personnel committee. His name appears in the 1996 federal court case Dawson v. New York Life Ins. Co. as a key decision-maker. He subsequently retired from New York Life.

name: Hansel, Stephen E.
title: Founder / Former CEO, Hibernia Corporation
notes: Stephen Arthur Hansel (August 13, 1947 - February 2024) was a banker born in Long Branch, NJ, educated at Wesleyan University (BA 1969) and UVA Darden School of Business (MBA 1971). He was CFO of Barnett Banks (Florida) before becoming CEO of Hibernia Bank (New Orleans) in 1992, where he turned the failing institution into Louisiana's largest bank with assets growing from $4B to $16B by 2000. He later ran Eclectic Investment Management and was president of the New Orleans Museum of Art (NOMA) board.
ngos: President, Board of Directors, New Orleans Museum of Art (NOMA)

name: Jacobes, Charley

title: Principal / Real Estate Investor
notes: Charley Jacobes (Charles Hand Jacobes, born January 1970) is based in Sacramento, California with a BA in Social Sciences from UC Berkeley (1988-1993). He is associated with Jacobes Properties, Inc. and Jacobes Investment Properties, LLC (established 2023), and has also worked in automotive sales management. He is the son (or brother) of Roy Chapman Jacobes.

name: Johnson, Charles W. III
title: Commercial Fisherman (retired)
notes: Charles W. 'Charlie' Johnson III (May 5, 1941 - May 9, 2024) was born in Portland, Maine and raised in Harpswell and Brunswick, ME. He began lobstering at age 13, became a full-time commercial fisherman after high school, and developed a high-seas swordfishing operation by 1974, acquiring the F/V Seneca in 1989. He fished internationally in Peru, Brazil, and Trinidad, and maintained seasonal fishing in Brazilian waters from 1996 to 2006 before retiring in 2014.

name: Lavis, William Henry IV

title: Partner / Employee Benefits Consultant
notes: William 'Bill' Henry Lavis IV started his employee benefits career with Canada Life in 1986, joined Sitzmann Insurance Agency (predecessor to SML) in 1988, and became a Partner in 1993. He has led the Employee Benefits practice at SML since 1988. He attended UC Berkeley. SML was acquired by Brown & Brown Insurance in November 2011.

(a family-owned retail grocery chain with 140+ western U.S. stores). He holds an economics degree from the University of San Francisco and has been a Director at the San Francisco SPCA Hospital since 2000.

name: Reed, Thomas C.
title: Former Secretary of the Air Force; Former Special Assistant to President Reagan for National Security
notes: Thomas Care Reed (March 1, 1934 - February 11, 2024) served as the 11th Secretary of the Air Force (1976-1977) under Presidents Ford and Carter, and as Director of the National Reconnaissance Office. He was a national security adviser to President Reagan before resigning in 1983 following an insider trading investigation. In the 1970s, he co-founded Clos du Bois winery in Sonoma County, which was sold to Hiram Walker in 1988 for ~$40 million. He authored 'At the Abyss: An Insider's History of the Cold War' (2004) and 'The Nuclear Express' (2009). He had a lifelong connection to Sonoma County, California.
political_donations: Active Republican fundraiser and delegate; organized Reagan's 1966 California gubernatorial campaign; RNC member for California 1968-1972. Specific FEC donation records not retrieved.

name: Rohr, James E.
employer: PNC Financial Services Group (retired); Carnegie Mellon University (Chairman, Board of Trustees)
title: Former Chairman and CEO, PNC Financial Services Group
notes: James E. Rohr joined PNC through its management development program in 1972 and served as CEO (2000-2013) and Chairman (2001-2014), growing it into one of the largest U.S. diversified financial services companies. He served as director of BlackRock, Inc., ATI, EQT Corporation, and on the RAND Board of Trustees. He championed PNC Grow Up Great, a $500M early childhood education initiative. He was Chairman of Carnegie Mellon University's Board of Trustees and a Notre Dame trustee.
ngos: Carnegie Mellon University Board of Trustees (Chairman); University of Notre Dame Board of Trustees; The Heinz Endowments (director); Horatio Alger Association (member); Committee Encouraging Corporate Philanthropy (director); RAND Corporation Board of Trustees
political_donations: PNC PAC contributed to both parties; individual FEC records not retrieved. PNC donated to National Republican Senatorial Committee and National Republican Congressional Committee per CREW reports.

name: Shea, Peter Jr.
title: President and CEO
notes: Peter Owen Shea Jr. is President and CEO of J.F. Shea Co., the California-based construction and real estate conglomerate (est. 1881 as a plumbing company). He succeeded John F. Shea as CEO in 2005. Under his leadership J.F. Shea operates Shea Homes (one of the nation's largest private homebuilders with operations in 11 states), Shea Properties (commercial real estate), and J.F. Shea Construction. He has an estimated net worth of $2.5 billion.

name: Shea, Peter Owen
employer: J.F. Shea Co., Inc. / J.F. Shea Construction Inc. (deceased)
title: Former President, J.F. Shea Construction Inc.; Former Executive VP, J.F. Shea Co.
notes: Peter Owen Shea Sr. (May 29, 1935 - October 25, 2023) was a co-founder of the modern J.F. Shea Co., Inc., along with brother Edmund H. Shea Jr. and cousin John F. Shea, who restructured the family firm in 1958. He was president of J.F. Shea Construction Inc. and executive VP of J.F. Shea Co. He attended Loyola High School (LA), earned a business degree at UC Berkeley and a civil engineering degree from USC. He was particularly known for leading major tunnel construction projects including the Arrowhead Tunnel in the San Bernardino Mountains.

name: Sitzmann, Gary Russell
employer: Sitzmann, Morris & Lavis Insurance Agency (SML) / Brown & Brown Insurance (retired)
title: Founder, SML; Vice President, Brown & Brown (retired)
notes: Gary Russell Sitzmann (b. ~1943) began his insurance career in 1965 after earning a degree from Armstrong College. He moved to Phoenix Mutual Life in 1969 and served as their National Sales Leader for seven years before founding SML in 1980. For over four decades he was a nationally recognized life insurance producer specializing in affluent client and executive benefit markets. He retired from SML/Brown & Brown in July 2021. He resides in Orinda, CA and was honored as Man of the Year by the Bay Area Tumor Institute in 2005.
ngos: Trustee, UC Berkeley Educational Foundation; Board member, Tahoe Lakefront Homeowners Association; National Association of Insurance and Financial Advisors (NAIFA)

name: Sitzmann, Matthew M.
employer: Castle Funds / Brown & Brown Insurance of Northern California (former)
title: Chairman of the Advisory Board, Castle Funds; Former EVP, Brown & Brown
notes: Matthew M. Sitzmann is the son of Gary Sitzmann and served as CEO of Sitzmann, Morris & Lavis Insurance Agency (SML) before its acquisition by Brown & Brown Insurance in November 2011. He then served as Executive Vice President and Profit Center Leader at Brown & Brown Insurance Services of California until September 2022. He became Chairman of the Advisory Board at Castle Funds in October 2022. He led SML operations from offices in Oakland, Lafayette, and Santa Rosa.

name: Sweeney, Joseph Edward III
title: Managing Partner / Director of Business Solutions
notes: Joseph Edward Sweeney III is a registered investment adviser (SEC IAPD CRD #1299368) and Managing Partner at Cornerstone Wealth Group, LLC in San Francisco. He holds degrees from Stanford University and Stanford Graduate School of Business and has over four decades of experience in financial advisory roles including prior service at LPL Financial. He is an Accredited Investment Fiduciary (AIF) and BEI Certified Exit Planner.

name: Tett, David
title: Founder and President
notes: David Tett is a Zimbabwean-born entrepreneur who founded Bushtracks Expeditions in 1989, a luxury African safari company headquartered in Healdsburg, California and Johannesburg, South Africa. Born and raised in Zimbabwe, he earned a degree in Microbiology in South Africa and began his career with the Agricultural Research Board before relocating to Northern California in 1991. He collaborates with his brothers Christopher and Nicholas who manage Bushtracks Africa.
ngos: Bushtracks Expeditions supports wildlife conservation and community development in Africa

name: Thomson, Peter A.
title: Chairman and Founder, Thomvest Ventures; Co-Chairman, Woodbridge Company
notes: Peter J. Thomson (born 1965) is a member of the Canadian Thomson family (of Thomson Reuters fame) and son of Kenneth Thomson. He founded Thomvest Ventures in 1996 as the Silicon Valley-based venture capital arm of the Thomson family, investing in fintech, cybersecurity, and AI with a $750M cross-stage fund. He is Co-Chairman of The Woodbridge Company (which controls 67.8% of Thomson Reuters) and a Director of Thomson Reuters since 1995. His net worth is estimated at $10.1 billion.

name: Tolling, Mads
employer: Self-employed (musician); Bob Weir's Wolf Bros / Wolf Pack Band
title: Violinist, Composer, Two-time Grammy Award Winner
notes: Mads Tolling (born July 5, 1980, Copenhagen, Denmark) is a Danish-American violinist and composer who graduated summa cum laude from Berklee College of Music in 2003. He won two Grammy Awards for Best Classical Crossover Album as a member of Turtle Island Quartet ('4+Four' 2005, 'A Love Supreme' 2007). He toured with Stanley Clarke's band (2003-2010) and since 2021 has been a featured member of Bob Weir's Wolf Bros/Wolf Pack Band, performing at Red Rocks, The Greek Theatre, and Radio City Music Hall. He lives in the San Francisco Bay Area.

name: Vail, Thomas Parker
title: Professor and Chair Emeritus, Department of Orthopaedic Surgery; Michael and Antoinette Pappas Endowed Chair
notes: Dr. Thomas Parker Vail, MD is an internationally recognized orthopedic surgeon specializing in hip and knee replacement. He earned his BS in Mechanical Engineering and Materials Science from Duke University (cum laude) and his MD from Loyola University Stritch School of Medicine, completing residency at Duke. He joined UCSF's Department of Orthopaedic Surgery as Chair in 2007, received the James L. Young endowed professorship in 2014, and the Pappas Endowed Chair in 2021. He is past President of the Knee Society and the American Association of Hip and Knee Surgeons.
ngos: Past President, Knee Society; Past President, American Association of Hip and Knee Surgeons; Board of Trustees, Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery (JBJS); Past VP, American Board of Orthopaedic Surgery
